---
import TutorialLayout from '../../layouts/TutorialLayout.astro';
import CodeGroup from '../../components/CodeGroup.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<TutorialLayout title="Refactoring with GSD" description="Use GSD's structured workflow to safely refactor existing code — extract modules, swap storage, and add tests without breaking anything.">

	<!-- Section 1: Why Refactoring Is Scary -->
	<section class="mb-16">
		<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-heading mb-4">Why Refactoring Is Scary</h2>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			In <a href={`${base}tutorials/building-features-with-gsd`} class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover transition-colors underline">Tutorial 2</a>, you built priorities, due dates, and filtering into the task tracker. It works. But look at the code — everything lives in a single file. The data model, storage logic, CLI commands, and display formatting are all tangled together. Adding the next feature means wading through 100+ lines of mixed concerns.
		</p>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			You know the code should be split into modules. You know the JSON file storage should be abstracted so you could swap it later. You know there should be tests. But refactoring working code is risky — especially when there are no tests to catch regressions.
		</p>
		<p class="text-text mb-6">
			This is where most refactoring goes wrong. Someone starts moving functions around, breaks something subtle, spends an hour debugging, and either gives up or ships it with a "this should be fine" commit message. GSD prevents this by treating refactoring as structured work — discussed, planned, verified at every step, and atomically committed so each change is independently revertable.
		</p>
	</section>

	<!-- Section 2: Planning the Refactor -->
	<section class="mb-16">
		<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-heading mb-4">Planning the Refactor</h2>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			Start by telling GSD what you want to accomplish. Use <code class="text-accent">/gsd-discuss-phase</code> to work through the approach before any code changes:
		</p>

		<div class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-surface p-6 mb-6">
			<p class="text-text-muted text-sm mb-2">Your prompt:</p>
			<p class="text-text font-mono text-sm">
				I want to refactor the task tracker. Extract the storage logic into its own module, separate the CLI layer from the business logic, and add tests to make sure nothing broke. The behavior should be identical after refactoring.
			</p>
		</div>

		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			GSD's discuss phase works through the gray areas: should tests come before or after the extraction? What does "identical behavior" mean — same output, same exit codes, same error messages? These decisions get recorded in <code class="text-accent">.planning/STATE.md</code>.
		</p>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			After discussion, <code class="text-accent">/gsd-plan-phase</code> creates atomic plans ordered by dependency. Refactoring order matters — you don't extract the CLI layer before the storage layer, because the CLI depends on how data access works.
		</p>

		<div class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-surface p-6 mb-6">
			<p class="text-text-muted text-sm mb-3">GSD's refactoring plans:</p>
			<div class="space-y-3">
				<div class="flex items-start gap-3">
					<span class="text-accent font-mono text-sm shrink-0 mt-0.5">Plan 1</span>
					<div>
						<p class="text-heading text-sm font-medium">Add tests to the existing code</p>
						<p class="text-text-muted text-sm">After this: test suite passes on the current single-file implementation — your safety net is in place</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="flex items-start gap-3">
					<span class="text-accent font-mono text-sm shrink-0 mt-0.5">Plan 2</span>
					<div>
						<p class="text-heading text-sm font-medium">Extract storage module</p>
						<p class="text-text-muted text-sm">After this: storage is behind a clean interface, all existing tests still pass</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="flex items-start gap-3">
					<span class="text-accent font-mono text-sm shrink-0 mt-0.5">Plan 3</span>
					<div>
						<p class="text-heading text-sm font-medium">Separate business logic from CLI</p>
						<p class="text-text-muted text-sm">After this: clean architecture — CLI is a thin shell, logic is independently testable, all tests pass</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>

		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			Notice Plan 1 comes first: <strong class="text-heading">tests before refactoring.</strong> This is the single most important lesson in this tutorial. Without tests, you're flying blind — every change could break something you won't notice until a user reports it. With tests, every plan has an instant verification: <em>did the tests still pass?</em>
		</p>
		<p class="text-text mb-6">
			GSD records this decision in <code class="text-accent">.planning/STATE.md</code>: "Write tests against the existing interface first, then refactor behind them. Tests verify behavior hasn't changed — they're the contract."
		</p>
	</section>

	<!-- Section 3: Plan 1 — Tests First -->
