	<section class="mb-16">
		<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-heading mb-4">What Made This Safe</h2>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			Let's be honest about what just happened. We took a working, single-file CLI and split it into three modules. That's the kind of change where things quietly break — an import path is wrong, a function signature changed, a field name got mistyped. Here's what GSD did differently:
		</p>

		<div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
			<div class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-surface p-5">
				<p class="text-heading font-medium mb-2">Tests came first, not last</p>
				<p class="text-text-muted text-sm">The tests were written against the working code before any refactoring started. They captured the real behavior — not the intended behavior. That distinction matters when you're changing how the code is organized but not what it does.</p>
			</div>
			<div class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-surface p-5">
				<p class="text-heading font-medium mb-2">One structural change per plan</p>
				<p class="text-text-muted text-sm">Plan 2 extracted storage. Plan 3 extracted business logic. We never did both at once. When tests fail after a single change, you know exactly what broke. When tests fail after two simultaneous changes, you're debugging a combinatorial explosion.</p>
			</div>
			<div class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-surface p-5">
				<p class="text-heading font-medium mb-2">Fresh context prevented confusion</p>
				<p class="text-text-muted text-sm">Each plan ran with a clean 200k-token context. Plan 3 didn't inherit stale assumptions from Plan 2's execution — it read the current code fresh. No "but I thought we changed that" confusion from accumulated context.</p>
			</div>
			<div class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-surface p-5">
				<p class="text-heading font-medium mb-2">Same tests, different structure</p>
				<p class="text-text-muted text-sm">The test suite didn't change between plans. It tested through the CLI interface, which means it verified behavior regardless of how the internals were organized. If the tests pass, the refactoring preserved the contract.</p>
			</div>
			<div class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-surface p-5">
				<p class="text-heading font-medium mb-2">Atomic commits for clean rollback</p>
				<p class="text-text-muted text-sm">Each plan produced one commit. If Plan 3 had broken something subtle, we'd revert that single commit — the storage extraction from Plan 2 would still be intact. No "revert everything and start over."</p>
			</div>
		</div>

		<p class="text-text mb-6">
			Contrast this with the typical refactoring experience: open the file, start moving things around, tests break (if they exist), fix the tests, realize another file depends on the old structure, fix that too, run the app, something's subtly wrong, spend 45 minutes debugging. GSD replaces that chaos with a sequence of small, verified steps.
		</p>
